    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix segmentation fault in X2AP dump_tree when eNB_name is NULL\n\n### Summary\nThe X2AP dump_tree function was dereferencing a NULL eNB_name pointer, causing segmentation faults when displaying eNB information. This occurred when eNB entries didn't have names assigned.\n\nAdditionally, the tree structure visualization was difficult to interpret due to lack of indentation. The recursive calls didn't show parent-child relationships clearly.\n\nThis fix handles NULL eNB names safely and adds proper indentation to visualize the tree hierarchy.\n\n### Changes\n- `openair2/X2AP/x2ap_eNB_management_procedures.c`: \n  - Added NULL check for eNB_name in printf statement\n  - Added indentation support using existing indent variable\n  - Created X2AP_DUMP_TREE_OUT macro for consistent formatting\n  - Restructured dump_tree to properly indent recursive calls\n\n### Reproduction\nTo reproduce the original issue:\n1. Run OAI5G with X2AP enabled\n2. Establish connections with eNBs that don't provide names\n3. Call dump_trees() function (typically via logging or debugging)\n4. Observe segmentation fault when dump_tree tries to print NULL eNB_name\n\nThe fix prevents the crash and shows properly indented tree structure making it easier to debug X2AP connections.\n"
}